    answer: "A new fear of sleeping alone can happen in typically developing 8–10-year-olds, especially during stressful transitions, but persistent bedtime fear, panic, or repeated night wakings may point to anxiety rather than a passing phase (AACAP, 2020). Talk to your pediatrician if it lasts more than a few weeks or affects daytime functioning."
  },
  {
    question: "Is it typical that my child worries constantly about school mistakes?",
    answer: "Frequent worry about getting things wrong can be common in 8–10-year-olds, but anxiety becomes more concerning when the worry is excessive, hard to stop, and causes tears, avoidance, perfectionism, or meltdowns over ordinary schoolwork (NIMH, 2023). Talk to your pediatrician if the worry is interfering with learning or family life."
  },
  {
    question: "Can anxiety look like anger in an 8 to 10 year old?",
    answer: "Yes — anxiety in 8–10-year-olds often looks like irritability, shutdowns, refusal, or anger rather than a child saying, 'I feel anxious' (AAP, 2020). If emotional outbursts happen mostly around school, social events, bedtime, or separation, anxiety may be part of the picture, and it is reasonable to discuss this with your pediatrician."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I make my child go to school if they are anxious?",
    answer: "In most cases, yes — school avoidance usually makes childhood anxiety stronger over time because avoidance teaches the brain that the feared situation is dangerous (AAP, 2020; AACAP, 2020). If school refusal is escalating, involve your pediatrician promptly so your child can get support before the pattern becomes entrenched."
  },
